===Etymology===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|もも}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=もも|-}}, from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|sort=もも|*momo}}. Mentioned in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2}}</ref>

Brought to Japan in antiquity, with pits found in prehistoric sites from the {{w|Yayoi period}}, 300 BCE - 300 CE. Mentioned as a [[food]] in documents from the {{w|Nara period|Nara}} and {{w|Heian period|Heian}} periods.<ref name="KDJ2"/>

Ultimate derivation unknown. Theories include the following.
* Possibly derived originally from a reduplication of {{m|ja|実|tr={{upright|Old Japanese}} mu, {{upright|modern Japanese}} mi||fruit}}, from the way that peaches often grow in clusters. However, the vowel shift seems unlikely given regular Japanese phonetic shifts. In addition, most reduplicated terms in Japanese have the {{m|ja|頭高型|tr=atamadaka-gata}} pitch accent pattern, starting high and falling, which differs from the {{m|ja|平板型|tr=heiban-gata}} pitch accent pattern of this term.
* Possibly cognate with {{cog|ojp|百|tr=momo||hundred; lots}}. However, this also has the {{m|ja|頭高型|tr=atamadaka-gata}} pitch accent pattern.
* Possibly a reduplication of {{m|ja|毛|tr=mo||hair}}, from the way that peaches are [[hairy]]. The term is spelled as {{m|ja|毛毛}} in some ancient documents. However, {{m|ja|毛}} was commonly used as [[man'yōgana]] for its phonetic value, in which cases its original Chinese meaning of {{m|en|hair}} is usually ignored.

None of the above possibilities seems very compelling. Given the archaeological evidence, this term probably predated Old Japanese and originated from among the {{w|Yayoi people}}, descendants of the local {{w|Jōmon people}} in the Japanese [[archipelago]] and {{w|Proto-Japonic language|Proto-Japonic-speaking}} migrants from the Korean [[peninsula]].<ref>{{cite-journal|work= w:Plos One|first1= Elisabeth|last1= de Boer|first2= Melinda A.|last2= Yang|first3= Aileen|last3= Kawagoe|first4= Gina L.|last4= Barnes|date= 5 May 2020|title= Japan considered from the hypothesis of farmer/language spread|titleurl= https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10427481/}}</ref>

Possibly related to {{m|ja|梅|tr={{upright|ancient}} mume, {{upright|modern}} ume||Japanese apricot, Japanese plum}}.

